body:
**What would you like added/supported?**

It would be nice if Verilator could optimized `2 ** x` (where `x` is unsigned) into `1 << x`. This currently works if the base is constant and `unsigned` (e.g. `32'd2`), but the optimization is not applied if the base is declared as signed.
This construct is quite common (even though one could argue people should just use an unsigned base for correctness).

```systemverilog
int unsigned x;

// optimized into 1 << X (left-shift)
assign opt1 = 32'd2 ** X;
assign opt2 = $unsigned(2) ** X;

// optimization missed
assign noopt1 = 2 ** X;
```

**Note about Signedness**

I am not sure about the required output type. As far as I can see, Verilator produces a signed output, but I am unsure whether this is correct. There is this comment in the source code which I don't understand fully:
https://github.com/verilator/verilator/blob/9b99d9697fd631d46b7bdaf0713a4b9d82348138/src/V3Width.cpp#L1499-L1501

In any case, this optimization can still work even if the output needs to be signed (I think), by converting the output back to a signed number after shifting.

There is also [this commit](https://github.com/verilator/verilator/commit/55ad95060996d3398ef8eee883f5ec71d935e731) which removed this optimization, and I assume there was some thought behind that. So we need to be careful to ensure a correct output type.

**What 'verilator --version' are you using?  Did you try it with the git master version?**

`Verilator 5.039 devel rev v5.038-1-g8ba7cec15` (very recent)

**May we assist you in trying to fix this in Verilator yourself?**

I am trying to prepare a patch for this.

